Q14: People not providing tests, not having a long track history of patches, people that tend to rewrite existing parts of the code
Q16:
It's always easier to do a careful review when there are few patches in the backlog. If there are many patches awaiting reviews, the eagerness of going through them all likely lowers the attentivness  of the reviewer and lowers the standard of acceptation.
In a way code reviews are political in that you don't want the project to be blocked, or to have to maintain a backlog of patches that you endlessly have to rework because of a nitpicky reviewer. This means you ask reviewers you trust to go over your code (and not necesseraly the reviewers that would make you rewrite everything several times) and try to dissociate personal preference in the code vs potential defects / issues a piece of code might introduce.

Q14: Largely inexperience or a focus on "just fixing my issue" and not caring about the bigger picture is the major reason for issue introduction. Some issues have been also from a more historical design standpoint and have required an evolution and mass consensus building to move beyond the current state, because there are many ways to do things, but also many ways that can also make it difficult or impossible to use security features, such as requiring additional configuration or parameters that vendors cannot automatically change or supply data for due to export controls.
Q16: Core review groups are diverse groups that look at the code and approve it to merge. Often it is easy to miss something when your in a mode of encouraging a new contributor to progress forward, which is honestly why we try to keep code contributions to a smaller size. They become more easy to consume and digest and ultimately reviewer's eyes do not glaze over. As a project leader, I get to be in that fun position of encouraging and trying to provide initial upfront secure design feedback, and then in implementation I have to work to get the code completely published into review before we can really start to fully review the full scope of changes, which sometimes ultimately means that some reviews are too quick, but are still insufficient to approve changes to merge in our code review model. This allows encouragement without approval to merge/land without multiple. This is not to say every new contributor gets a free pass while getting their feature or fix into the review process, sometimes when we observe changes that are extremely insecure, we'll go ahead and block those changes and attempt to have a dialog with the contributor.
